Inhibitors that specifically target integration have also been approved for the treatment of HIV infection. Since integrase is a necessary enzyme for the replication step involving the integration of host cell DNA to the viral genome, it has become a validated target for developing anti-HIV agents (
 Hazuda et al., 2000; 
 Pommier et al., 2005; 
 Antonelli and Turriziani, 2012). New integrase inhibitors targeting Gag, as an antiviral target, indicated auspicious effects both in preclinical and clinical trials (
 Min et al., 1999b; 
 Pommier et al., 2005; 
 Grinsztejn et al., 2007).
